Welcome to my PoC page! 

Here is an example of how I "diagnose bugs/code errors", so you can view exactly what you are dealing with when it comes to my services.

Example Error: 

Cannot find module '@/components/Navbar'
Require stack:
- /app/.next/server/pages/index.js
- /app/node_modules/next/dist/server/require.js
- /app/node_modules/next/dist/server/load-components.js
- /app/node_modules/next/dist/server/api-utils/node.js

Diagnostic: 

Alright — I can see exactly why this is blowing up.
The import path @/components/Navbar is using a path alias (@/) that hasn’t actually been defined anywhere in the project.
Here’s what’s happening under the hood:
Next.js hands the import to Webpack
Webpack checks your tsconfig.json or jsconfig.json for path aliases
It looks for a mapping for @/*
It finds nothing
So it has no idea where @/components/Navbar is supposed to live
The module resolver gives up and throws the error you’re seeing
In other words:
Your code is using a shortcut that the build system doesn’t understand.
This is why it works on some machines (like macOS) but fails instantly in CI or production.
Root Cause
The alias @/ is missing from your config.
Or the file components/Navbar doesn’t exist at the expected path.
Fix
To resolve this cleanly:
Open tsconfig.json or jsconfig.json
Add the correct alias mapping:
json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "baseUrl": ".",
    "paths": {
      "@/*": ["./*"]
    }
  }
}
Ensure the file actually exists at:
Code
/components/Navbar.(js|tsx)
Clear .next cache
Rebuild
Once the alias is defined, the resolver knows exactly where to look — and the error disappears.
Outcome
Build succeeds.
Component loads correctly.
No more module resolution failures.

Thank you for reading!
